{
  "comment_text": {
    "sn10.2:1.2": "The suffix <i lang='pi' translate='no'>-nāmaka</i> is a slight. Compare “Senior in name only” (<a href='https://suttacentral.net/sn21.10/en/sujato#1.2'>SN 21.10:1.2</a>) and <i lang='pi' translate='no'>nāmaka</i> in the sense “mere words” (<a href='https://suttacentral.net/mn80/en/sujato#15.5'>MN 80:15.5</a>, <a href='https://suttacentral.net/mn99/en/sujato#10.5'>MN 99:10.5</a>). His verse is similar to that of Māra in <a href='https://suttacentral.net/sn4.14/en/sujato'>SN 4.14</a>. ",
    "sn10.2:3.1": "",
    "sn10.2:3.2": "The Buddha avoids <i lang='pi' translate='no'>nāmaka</i> and politely calls him “Sakka”. ",
    "sn10.2:3.4": "Accepting the variant <i lang='pi' translate='no'>ananukampituṁ</i> at <a href='https://suttacentral.net/ne37/en/sujato#194.4'>Ne 37:194.4</a>, which is endorsed by that text’s commentaries. The text as stands enjoins lack of compassion, which cannot be right. "
  },
